{"notes": "Last meeting I ran a clear "yields lower" view, anchored on term_premium -0.60 (10y falling sharply) and balance_sheet -0.45 (runoff pulling yields up but I read balance sheet as shrinking, i.e., its own measure falling). Both of those have now moved against that setup. Term_premium's own analyst has flipped from -0.60 to flat: the 63d/252d decline has stalled, DGS10 is consolidating at 1.57-1.58%, with a mild 21d uptick — exactly the kind of stabilization my prior falsifier flagged (sustained move back toward/above 1.65-1.70% would flip me; we're not there, but the "down" thesis is dead). Balance_sheet flipped hard too: assets printed a 13-observation high, above the 13w average, with positive 4w/13w momentum — my own stated falsifier ("rebound condition") triggered. That's a genuine, named reversal, not just a price wiggle: two of my three previously-loaded drivers independently turned within this meeting.

Inflation continues to firm gently (core PCE yoy up to 1.60%, headline yoy near 12m highs) — a modest upward pull on yields via inflation compensation, though inflation_expectations (breakevens) itself is flat/range-bound, which caps how much this argues for higher yields nominally. Labor tightness is flat/noisy, no directional push. Financial conditions flat, no impulse either way. The term_premium analyst also flags it lacks balance_sheet and financial_conditions inputs directly — but balance_sheet's own turn (toward "up," meaning shrinking reinvestment support, i.e., upward yield pressure) reinforces rather than contradicts the stabilization in term_premium's own reading.

Net: the strongest deflationary-yield forces from last meeting (falling term premium, shrinking balance sheet) have both stalled or reversed. Nothing here argues for a strong new "yields much higher" call, but the prior "yields lower" position is no longer supported by fresh evidence — the honest move is to flatten to near-neutral with a very slight upward lean, not to keep pressing lower.", "drivers": [{"driver": "balance_sheet", "conviction": 0.35, "why": "Own analyst flipped down->up: 13-obs high print, above 13w avg, positive 4w/13w momentum triggered stated falsifier."}, {"driver": "term_premium", "conviction": 0.05, "why": "Analyst flipped -0.60 to flat: DGS10 decline stalled near 1.57-1.58, 21d modest uptick, still low range position."}, {"driver": "inflation", "conviction": 0.4, "why": "Core PCE yoy climbing to 1.60%, headline near 12m highs; carried through from analyst's up call, gentle persistent firming."}, {"driver": "labor_tightness", "conviction": 0.0, "why": "Flat/noisy 4.80-5.10% band, no directional signal per analyst; no view change."}, {"driver": "financial_conditions", "conviction": 0.0, "why": "NFCI pinned near -0.37 for months, no momentum either direction; stays flat."}], "leaned_on": ["balance_sheet", "term_premium", "inflation"], "discounted": [{"driver": "labor_tightness", "why": "Flat, range-bound over a year, no rate-axis signal."}, {"driver": "financial_conditions", "why": "Extremely stable NFCI, no directional pressure to lean on."}], "falsifier": "A fresh sustained decline in DGS10 back toward/below 1.50% or resumed balance-sheet contraction below the 13w average would revive the yields-lower call.", "confidence": 0.45, "risks": [{"tag": "duration", "text": "Term premium stabilization could be noise near cycle lows rather than a genuine trend change."}, {"tag": "policy", "text": "Balance-sheet uptick may be a technical bounce within ongoing net runoff, not a real reversal."}, {"tag": "positioning", "text": "Panel is genuinely split/stale in places (curve_slope, inflation_expectations flat), weakening conviction in either direction."}]}
